## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2020 Blackbaud data breach** — a cloud software provider used by hundreds of healthcare organizations, nonprofits, and universities. Attackers gained access to Blackbaud's systems and exfiltrated data belonging to thousands of Blackbaud customers — including patient and donor data from numerous healthcare organizations that had no direct security failure of their own.

What made this case a perfect illustration of enterprise risk thinking is the supply chain dimension. The affected healthcare organizations had done their own security work — they had policies, they had technical controls, they had compliance programs. But they had a third-party vendor with access to their data, and that vendor had a security failure. The enterprise risk register entry for "third-party vendor security failure" was not a theoretical concern. It materialized across hundreds of organizations simultaneously because of one vendor's breach.

Blackbaud paid a $49.5 million settlement to state attorneys general in 2023. Many of the affected healthcare organizations faced their own notification and compliance obligations even though the breach originated entirely outside their environments.

That case reinforced for me why enterprise risk assessment cannot stop at the organization's own systems. The risk landscape extends to every vendor, partner, and third party with access to your data or your infrastructure. Understanding that landscape — and building it into the risk management strategy — is what distinguishes a mature GRC program from one that only manages the risks it directly controls.

